<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-12-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-12-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="82" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Wu</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-12-30"><hi rend="italic">December 30,
                                    1901</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 196.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of your note No. 220, of the 16th instant, expressing your
                            appreciation of the justness of the course pursued by the Treasury
                            Department in the case of the Chiness student Tong Tseng.</p>
                        <p>In reply, I have the honor to inform you that a copy of your note has
                            been sent to the Secretary of the Treasury for his information.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>